		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A Guide to Companions - Part 2: Brothers in Arms<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.75)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15286'>David "Wyvern" Cauwenbergh</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15286&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 25, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> First of all, thanks to all the people who&#8217;ve read and reviewed my previous article, you&#8217;ve all been a great help!  I&#8217;ve noticed the article included a couple of mistakes, so I&#8217;ll try and do my best to avoid them this time =)<br />
<br />
Okay, let&#8217;s get on with it then.  In my previous article I&#8217;ve discussed Aragorn and some cards that work fine with him.  In this article, I&#8217;ll have a look at two other &#8220;valiant men of the West&#8221;: Boromir and Faramir, this time I&#8217;ll try to go a little bit more into detail.  I&#8217;ve also included a section for beginning players willing to build a Ring bound Ranger deck (check somewhere near the end of the article).  In fact (and as I mentioned in the first part) this whole article is intended for beginning players&#8230; still I hope more experienced players will find a couple of useful things in here too.<br />
<br />
Enough with the rant, let&#8217;s start with Boromir.  There are currently three different versions of the unfortunate lad out there.  <br />
<br />
Boromir, Son of Denethor:<br />
<br />
Even though this guy might seem the least appealing of the three (he&#8217;s the only one that&#8217;s not a Ranger by the way), his ability to exert and give a hobbit strength +3 might come in very handy indeed.  Imagine your ring bearer desperately fighting for his life and about to be overwhelmed&#8230; the extra strength might just be enough to prevent this from happening.  Hey, thanks to Boromir&#8217;s ability, your little ones might even win a couple of skirmishes too&#8230; good enough for me.  <br />
<br />
What cards should I play on him? <br />
Boromir&#8217;s an unbound companion. Play more than two cards on him and he&#8217;ll be the target of that nasty Grima Wormtongue&#8230; Better to prevent this from happening&#8230;<br />
In this case, I&#8217;ll give him a hand weapon in order to make him win a couple of skirmishes.  The Blade of Gondor will do fine, even though you might go for an ordinary Sword as well since Boromir will be exerting to give those hobbits strength bonuses anyway.<br />
The second card that might work well with him is the Saga of Elendil.  First of all, it gives +1 vitality, which means you can exert him up to three times and give a hobbit up to+9 strength! (yeah right, you&#8217;d better make sure you&#8217;re able to heal him the turn after that =). Secondly, you can discard it for an extra strength bonus.  And that&#8217;s a good thing with all those dangerous minions out there&#8230;<br />
Well, there are in fact many cards that can be played on Boromir and you&#8217;ll find a couple more examples below.  These two are just a matter of personal preference.<br />
<br />
Boromir, Lord of Gondor:<br />
<br />
Try and overwhelm this guy!  Even without any equipment the Lord can handle a total strength of twenty.  Give him a piece of crappy armor and assign him to that new Balrog.  He&#8217;ll take a wound, end of skirmish!  Against swarm decks, make him Defender +1 with Elendil&#8217;s Valor and take on the two biggest minions you can see =)<br />
<br />
What cards should I play on him?<br />
Well, a piece of armor I&#8217;d say and this time, do give him his Blade of Gondor.  Exert him during a skirmish, wound an Orc or Uruk-Hai, simple as that.  The fact that he&#8217;s got the Aragorn signet means you can heal him each turn with Aragorn, King in Exile.<br />
<br />
Boromir, Defender of Minas Tirith:<br />
<br />
This one goes into my HiDaN deck.  Exert him for cards like Defend it and Hope or Help in Doubt and need and heal him during the Fellowship phase.  Even though this comes at the cost of two twilight, it&#8217;s often worth it.  <br />
In open you can always use him in combination with Aragorn, HttWC and heal him for free...  <br />
<br />
What cards should I play on him?<br />
The Blade of Gondor is a must indeed.  The other card (still taking Grima into account here&#8230;) is entirely up to you (even though I&#8217;d go for the Horn in open).<br />
<br />
<br />
Boromir&#8217;s other Gear:<br />
<br />
Now let&#8217;s discuss some of this guy&#8217;s other possessions shall we?<br />
<br />
Boromir&#8217;s Cloak:<br />
Nah, haven&#8217;t seen this one in many decks.  I&#8217;m wondering how many Weather Conditions are out there anyway&#8230;  Good to get rid of Saruman&#8217;s Snows, not worth to put in your deck in my opinion&#8230;<br />
<br />
Boromir&#8217;s Gauntlets:<br />
This one is so cool when your opponent isn&#8217;t paying attention&#8230; Imagine your opponent sitting there, staring at you, grinning like mad and throwing another one of those Balrogs in your face.  Unfortunately for him, he was so excited he didn&#8217;t notice he just wasted his last point of twilight.  Exert one of your men from Gondor, end of skirmish&#8230; Your turn to laugh now.  If only my opponent were stupid enough to allow me to use these little trinkets&#8230;<br />
<br />
Shield of Boromir:<br />
Quite decent, actually.  One less archery and your opponent loses his strength bonuses from weapons during skirmishes involving Boromir.  Nothing more, nothing less. Might help you win a couple more skirmishes for that Ithilien Trap though&#8230;<br />
<br />
Athelas:<br />
Same as with Gorn in the previous article:<br />
Good against those blade tips, black breaths and other nasty conditions that play on companions &#8211; in fact, it&#8217;s the only sort of condition removal Gondor has.<br />
The fact it can be used to heal too makes it quite useful in many decks&#8230;<br />
<br />
Horn of Boromir:<br />
Excellent card! Unfortunately it&#8217;s so broken it has been banned from Standard.  Use the Horn in combination with a bunch of Elven or Hobbit allies and let those guys take all the punishment for you.  Use it in combination with Defender of Minas Tirith; more exertions, more sacrificial lambs =)<br />
<br />
There are of course dozens of other cards that can be used with our valiant friend here.  But I&#8217;ll stop here since I still have another one of those companions and a deck type to discuss!<br />
Time to meet our Ring bound Ranger!<br />
<br />
Faramir, Son of Denethor<br />
<br />
Well, let&#8217;s see what Denethor&#8217;s other son has got to offer.  This guy fits in many different deck types.  I wouldn&#8217;t recommend using him in a Ring-bound Ranger deck though, since the other two versions are far better suited for this kind of deck.  <br />
The fact that your opponent&#8217; minions won&#8217;t be able to use skirmish events or use skirmish special abilities is quite decent though.  Mauhúr won&#8217;t be able to prevent trackers from taking wounds for example, nor can a Moria guard commander use his ability to give a strength bonus to your opponent&#8217;s minions.  These are just a couple examples, but like I said, this version of Faramir is decent enough.  What&#8217;s more, Faramir is ring-bound so no need to watch out for Grima Wormtongue!  <br />
<br />
Faramir, Ithilien Ranger<br />
<br />
The healing this guy provides is always welcome of course.  Even though he isn&#8217;t as good as the Captain of Gondor, the Ithilien Ranger might be a good option for beginning players who want to build a ring-bound ranger deck (more on that below) and who don&#8217;t own a copy of the rare Faramir.  Make sure to put him in your starting fellowship, together with Mablung or, even better, a Ranger of Ithilien.  <br />
<br />
Faramir, Captain of Gondor<br />
<br />
Well, to be honest, I think this one is the most useful of the three, especially in Ring-bound Ranger decks since they rely on making minions roaming with cards like Ancient Roads and Gondorian ranger, the strength bonus this guy gets is almost guaranteed.  Give him a sword and he&#8217;ll be able to win most skirmishes.  Like the Ithilien Ranger, make sure to put him in your starting fellowship together with a Ranger of Ithilien or Mablung.<br />
Time to take a look at Faramir&#8217;s gear I guess&#8230;<br />
<br />
Faramir&#8217;s gear<br />
<br />
Faramir&#8217;s Cloak<br />
A must in a Ring-bound ranger deck I&#8217;d say.  Every minion skirmishing a ring-bound man has its strength reduced by 1.  Well, this certainly helps you rangers win a couple more skirmishes and that&#8217;s always handy when you need those tokens for that Ithilien trap.  <br />
<br />
Faramir&#8217;s Bow<br />
Another excellent card that has (besides the fact that it makes Faramir an archer) in my opinion more in common with the Blade of Gondor than with Aragorn&#8217;s bow.  Extremely useful, even though it doesn&#8217;t provide you with aimed archery.  <br />
<br />
Boromir&#8217;s Broken horn - AKA Boromir, my Brother<br />
Faramir has sure got a couple of nice tricks up his sleeve.  One condition, three advantages!  First of all, Faramir gets an extra point of vitality (a &#8220;bonus exertion&#8221; for Faramir&#8217;s bow or cards like defend it and hope).  Secondly, it allows you to give your Ring-bound men the strength bonus they need to win their skirmishes.  Last but not least, it helps with the card cycling.  Oh, forgot one, it&#8217;s absolutely free&#8230;<br />
<br />
Sure, I know there are more cards out there, but, for the moment, I found these three to be the most relevant here.  Time to move on to the next topic&#8230;<br />
<br />
Deck Focus: The Ring-Bound Ranger Deck<br />
<br />
So, you&#8217;re new to the game and trying to build yourself a Ring-bound Ranger deck?<br />
Best way to get started is to get your hands on one of those Faramir starter decks.  <br />
Got yourself one?  Okay, time to have a look at its contents then&#8230;  We&#8217;ll start from there and make a few changes, as to make the deck a little more suited for competitive play.<br />
<br />
Your Ring-Bearer: <br />
Frodo, Tired Traveller will do fine in this kind of deck.  Since you&#8217;ll be playing a lot of Ring-bound companions, you can make excellent use of his ability.  You&#8217;ll be able to bid high enough (3-4) to go first and remove the burdens afterwards by playing your ring-bound companions.  <br />
Unless you managed to get your hands on one of those rare rings (tengwar set, anyone?), the Ruling Ring will do fine for now.<br />
<br />
Your Companions:<br />
Let&#8217;s first have a look at what companions are included in the deck:<br />
Faramir, Ithilien Ranger x2, Sméagol, Poor Creature, Sam Nice Sensible Hobbit, Ranger of Ithilien x3 and Anborn, Skilled Huntsman x2<br />
<br />
Okay, time to decide what companions will be in our starting fellowship:<br />
Since both Faramir, Ithilien Ranger and the Ranger of Ithilien have their twilight cost reduced while in the starting fellowship, we&#8217;ll take these.  It would be a good idea to replace this version of Faramir with the Captain of Gondor as soon as possible, since he&#8217;s far more useful. (good thing is he&#8217;ll be part of the &#8216;Where&#8217;s Tom Bombadil?&#8217; promotion!)<br />
<br />
Our other companions:<br />
Since we&#8217;ll be trying to make the opponent&#8217;s minions roaming, we&#8217;ll take the two other copies of the Ranger of Ithilien and put them into our deck.  The fact that they get a strength bonus then will come in very handy indeed.<br />
<br />
Hmm, I&#8217;d suggest you drop Anborn, Skilled Huntsman.  His ability isn&#8217;t that useful after all, since he needs to win a skirmish first in order to trigger his game text.  With a basic strength of six and no strength bonuses against roaming minions, that isn&#8217;t likely to happen, so let&#8217;s replace him with two copies of the Gondorian Ranger.  This guy always augments the site number of minions skirmishing ring-bound rangers, making them roaming.  That&#8217;s exactly what your Rangers of Ithilien need!<br />
<br />
Sam, Nice Sensible Hobbit: let&#8217;s replace him with another version of Sam that might come in handy when your opponent&#8217;s playing a swarm deck (Moria, Sauron,&#8230;): Sam, Proper Poet.  Even though he&#8217;ll probably get killed early in the game, he&#8217;ll be able to take care of two of your opponent&#8217;s minions.  <br />
<br />
Sméagol, poor Creature: Well, he certainly helps with card cycling and might even win a skirmish or two.  Let&#8217;s keep him =).<br />
<br />
Since there are only 24 FP cards in the starter deck (and since we&#8217;ll be playing 30), let&#8217;s add a couple more companions.  <br />
Mablung, Soldier of Gondor seems a good idea.  His ability to exhaust a roaming minion he is skirmishing is very useful.  Think about all those Isengard orcs with the ability to exert during the regroup phase, forcing you to wound your companions (and since they usually have a high vitality, they&#8217;ll be exerting a lot!).  <br />
Another good choice is Aragorn, Ranger of the North (he&#8217;s rare but you can find him in the Tengwar set =).  He&#8217;s excellent against swarm decks, and he&#8217;s a ranger too so he can help trigger Ancient Roads (see below).  Let&#8217;s include two copies of this guy.  <br />
<br />
Now that we&#8217;ve got our companions, let&#8217;s give them some equipment, shall we:<br />
In the starter deck there are two Ranger&#8217;s bows and three swords of Gondor.  They&#8217;ll do for now.  You might wish to replace one of the bows with Faramir&#8217;s bow if you were lucky enough to get one of those.  <br />
We&#8217;ll need some healing too of course.  I guess three copies of Athelas should do.  These will replace two of the three hobbit swords in the deck.  Hold on to the other Hobbit Sword (or replace it with a frying pan) and give it to Frodo. <br />
<br />
Conditions:<br />
There are two conditions in the deck: Don&#8217;t look at Them and Ancient Roads.  Let&#8217;s drop Don&#8217;t look at Them and add two more copies of Ancient Roads.  This deck relies on making your opponent&#8217;s minions roaming, and the Ancient Roads do just that.<br />
<br />
Events:<br />
Okay, there&#8217;s room for 7 more cards.  First of all, let&#8217;s add some pumps.  War and Valor seems a good choice, strength +3 and damage +1 against roaming minions is great.  Let&#8217;s add three copies of this card.  <br />
Now, what if your opponent is playing Bill Ferny and some nasty Nazgul?  We&#8217;ll need a card to get rid of the sneering fellow who can just ruin our entire strategy.  That&#8217;s why we&#8217;ll be putting three copies of Defend it and Hope in our Deck.  The fact that it works great against Uruks is always handy too&#8230;<br />
For our last card, we&#8217;ll be giving our Ring-bearer some extra protection with Severed his Bonds.<br />
<br />
Well, this is what our deck looks like now:<br />
<br />
Starting:<br />
Frodo, Tired Traveller<br />
The one Ring, the Ruling Ring<br />
Faramir, Ithilien Ranger (or even better, Captain of Gondor)<br />
Ranger of Ithilien<br />
Gondorian Ranger x2<br />
Aragorn, Ranger of the North x2<br />
Mablung, Soldier of Gondor<br />
Sam, Proper Poet<br />
Smeagol, Poor Creature<br />
<br />
Ranger&#8217;s Bow x2<br />
Sord of Gondor x3<br />
Hobbit sword (or frying pan)<br />
Athelas x3<br />
<br />
Ancient Roads x4<br />
<br />
War and Valor x3<br />
Defend it and hope x3<br />
Severed his bonds<br />
<br />
<br />
While describing Faramir&#8217;s gear, I&#8217;ve already mentioned three other cards that work well with this kind of deck: Faramir&#8217;s Bow, his cloak and Boromir, my brother.  Here&#8217;s a couple of other cards that might come in handy too:<br />
Ithilien Trap, Swordsman of the Northern Kingdom, new errand, Ruins of Osgiliath, Citadel of the Stars and Curse them.  There are many cards that work fine with Ring-bound Rangers.  Now, it&#8217;s up to you to discover which you like best&#8230;<br />
<br />
Now, that&#8217;s it for now I guess.  I do hope you enjoyed it!  In the next article Part 3&#8211; Wielder of the Flame, I&#8217;ll be discussing Gandalf and his pet the Balrog.  Have fun I&#8217;d say and see you next time!<br />
<br />
Cheers from Belgium!<br />
